+      "title": "17% to 33%: When \"Hallucination-Free\" Tools Still Hallucinate",
+      "content": "Stanford's RegLab and Human-Centered AI Institute tested two AI legal research products that marketed themselves as hallucination-free. The 2024 study evaluated Lexis+ AI and Thomson Reuters' AI legal research tools against a benchmark of legal queries with known correct answers. The tools hallucinated between 17% and 33% of the time. Both products had been pitched to lawyers as solving the hallucination problem.\n\nThe researchers defined a hallucination as any answer that was either factually wrong or that cited a source the tool got wrong. The errors were not edge cases. Tools fabricated case names, misquoted holdings, and cited statutes that did not say what the tool claimed. Two of the country's largest legal-tech vendors shipped products with that error rate, alongside marketing claims that did not hold up.\n\nThe Stanford finding is the closest public analog to what the Discernment competency asks each pilot participant to develop. Vendor claims about reliability do not transfer to your specific task without verification. A tool can be useful 80% of the time and still produce errors at a rate that, if untouched, embarrasses your team and your scholars. The 17% to 33% range is the empirical case for keeping a human verifier in the loop on work that reaches a scholar, a partner, a funder, or the board.\n\nThe pilot's working assumption is that AI changes the speed of drafting, the breadth of input synthesis, and the floor of staff capacity. The standard your work has to meet stays the same. Stanford's 1-in-6 rate is what that standard costs to ignore.",
+      "tryThis": "Take one AI output you used this week. Pick one factual claim in it. Verify the claim from the original source. If the claim was correct, note what you would have lost by skipping that step. If the claim was wrong, note where it would have surfaced if you had not caught it. Bring one example to AI Friday.",
+      "resource": "https://arxiv.org/abs/2405.20362",
+      "sourceNotes": "Claim: Stanford's RegLab and HAI tested two AI legal research tools marketed as hallucination-free | Source: VERIFIED (Magesh, V., Surani, F., Dahl, M., Suzgun, M., Manning, C.D., Ho, D.E. \"Hallucination-Free? Assessing the Reliability of Leading AI Legal Research Tools,\" Stanford RegLab + Stanford HAI, May 2024, arXiv:2405.20362)\nClaim: The tools hallucinated between 17% and 33% of the time | Source: VERIFIED (Magesh et al. 2024 abstract and Stanford HAI summary: \"legal hallucinations are alarmingly prevalent, occurring between 17% and 33% of the time, depending on the tool\")\nClaim: Products tested were Lexis+ AI and Thomson Reuters' AI legal research tools | Source: VERIFIED (Magesh et al. 2024 — products evaluated include Lexis+ AI, Westlaw AI-Assisted Research, and Ask Practical Law AI)\nClaim: Stanford HAI summarized the failure rate as \"1 out of 6\" | Source: VERIFIED (Stanford HAI blog post title: \"AI on Trial: Legal Models Hallucinate in 1 out of 6 (or More) Benchmarking Queries,\" May 23, 2024)\nClaim: Hallucinations included fabricated case names, misquoted holdings, and incorrect statutory citations | Source: VERIFIED (Magesh et al. 2024 categorized errors as \"misgrounded responses\" and \"misleading statements,\" with specific examples of fabricated case names and misattributed holdings)\nClaim: Discernment is the Week 4 competency in the pilot | Source: GROUNDED (pilot_hub.html Week 4 discussion prompt block, labeled \"WEEK 4 — DISCERNMENT (Part 1)\")\nClaim: The pilot expects human verification on outputs that reach a scholar, partner, funder, or board | Source: GROUNDED (Framework_for_AI_Fluency_v1.5.md and pilot_hub.html — Diligence and Discernment competencies; matches 4-tier data classification model in data_tier_practice.html where higher-sensitivity tiers require explicit verification)\nEditorial: Framing the Stanford study as \"the closest public analog\" to the Discernment competency is Preston's pedagogical move tying an external empirical finding to the pilot's audit norms.\nEditorial: \"Empirical case for keeping a human verifier in the loop\" is Preston's synthesis applying the Stanford rate to DC CAP's risk surface (scholar, partner, funder, board).\nEditorial: The closing arc — \"AI changes... The standard your work has to meet stays the same... what that standard costs to ignore\" — is Preston's pedagogical close, deflationary by design.\nAdversarial review 20260501: Em-dash count: 0. Banned phrases scanned and absent: leverage, utilize, delve, navigate, landscape, ecosystem, synergy, robust, holistic, stakeholders, foster, enhance, align, transformative, empower, spearhead, myriad, multifaceted, nuanced, pivotal, unpack, deep dive, however, moreover, furthermore, additionally, serves as, stands as, represents, functions as, at the end of the day, move the needle, to be clear, make no mistake, doing the heavy lifting, the real question, what most people miss, groundbreaking, game-changing, revolutionary, showcase, underscore, passionate about, excited to share. Contrastive \"not X, but Y\" constructions: 0 (\"errors were not edge cases\" is a simple negation, not a contrastive). Rhetorical questions in body: 0. Declarative open: yes (\"Stanford's RegLab and Human-Centered AI Institute tested...\"). Word count main body: 258 (within 240–280 band). Try This word count: 59 (within 40–80 band). Each paragraph carries a concrete numeric anchor (17–33%, edge-cases negation, 80% / 17–33%, 1-in-6). Closing returns to pilot-policy implication.",
