     {
       "category": "trends",
       "content": "Anthropic released its March 2026 Economic Index report this spring, the third large-scale dataset on how Claude actually gets used. One finding sits directly in DC CAP's lane. Educational instruction tasks (coursework support, tutoring, instructional material development) rose from 9% to 13% of all Claude conversations. That is the fastest-growing task category in the Index. On Claude.ai specifically, educational instruction now accounts for 16% of conversations, four times the rate seen on the API. Education has moved into Claude's mainstream.\n\nThe augmentation share moved with it. 57% of conversations were augmentation in the current Index, where the user iterates with Claude through multiple turns of refinement. 43% were automation, where the user delegates a task and accepts the output. This is up from a 52/45 split in the prior Index, a meaningful shift in the direction of collaboration.\n\nTwo implications for the pilot. First, the kind of work DC CAP staff do (coaching, communication, instruction, family-facing explanation) is the work Claude is being adopted for fastest in the wild. The pilot is running with that trend. Second, the augmentation share rising is consistent with what the pilot has been teaching. Multi-turn collaboration produces better output on tasks where the standard depends on judgment.\n\nThe Economic Index gives the pilot a market check. The same job-shaped tasks DC CAP is bringing into Claude (drafting, explanation, structured feedback) are the ones the broader user base is converging on. The strategic question for Week 4 is what your team's split looks like, and whether it should.",
